bib_record.title: Fission in the reaction of 12-C with 209-Bi at 73.4 and 84.2 MeV

free_txt: Journal of Radioanalytical and Nuclear Chemistry
Fission product yield studies in the reaction of
73.4 and 84.2 MeV 12-C with 209-Bi have been carried
out using gamma ray spectrometry. The cross sections
for the production of fission products have been
determined. The yield distribution of fission products
was found to be symmetric and broad with FWHM around
25 mass units and peak near mass 107.7 and 107.0.
The average number of neutrons emitted per fission
have been found to be around 5.5 at 73.4 MeV and
7.1 at 84.2 MeV respectively
The errors listed are the standard deviations
between the results from five different irradiations
and various gamma rays.
These errors include the systematic errors added
quadratically due to:
detector efficiency (up to 5%),
fluctuation in the beam current (up to 5%),
error in the target thickness (up to 5%),
collection efficiency of fission
fragments (up to 5%) and
* gamma-ray abundances
Samples were irradiated for a suitable
length of time so as to determine both the short and
long lived fission products.
In each irradiation the decay of the gamma ray
peak of the fission products were followed for
suitable length of time so as to have minimum error
due to counting statistics.
The cumulative production cross section was determined
for most of the mass chains. In case of shielded nuclei
independent production cross section was determined.
Targets of super pure 209-Bi were prepared by vacuum
evaporation on 25.4 mumeter super pure aluminium
foil. Targets of 0.84 mg/cm**2 of bismuth were used
for Irradiation.  In order to avoid the cross
contamination of fission products due to large activity
of direct reaction products, the 209-Bi target was
covered with a 0.76 mumeter super pure aluminium foil.
This will allow the fission products to pass and will
prevent the reaction products.  The whole assembly was
put in a target holder and irradiated for a suitable
length of time with 77 MeV and 87.5 MeV 12-C particle
beam of ~100 nano-ampere. The incident 12-C energy
on the bismuth targets were 73.4 MeV and 84.2 MeV.
Bismuth targets and aluminium catchers were
separated from each other carefully to avoid cross
contamination. Aluminium catchers were mounted
separately on perspex plates in suitable geometry for
gamma ray spectrometry using HPGe detector system.
Data taken from  p.553 of main reference.
Total fission product cross section in the reaction of
12-C with 209-Bi at 73.4 and 84.2 MeV was determined by
integrating the product yields for all the mass chains
in 209Bi(12C,f) and was found to be around 473 and
814 mb for 73.4 MeV and 84.2 MeV respectively.
